      "root_cause_cluster": "runtime_seam_overuse"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
      "identifier": "sysconfig_any_section_leak",
      "summary": "The `SysConfig` section abstraction relies on `any`-typed mutation and a large registry, which weakens interface honesty and obscures domain boundaries.",
      "related_files": [
        "goseg/structs/configs.go",
        "goseg/config/config_update_registry.go",
        "goseg/defaults/defaults.go",
        "goseg/main.go"
      ],
      "evidence": [
        "`SysConfig.Section` and `SysConfig.UpdateSection` in `configs.go` expose dynamic access/mutation via `any` and descriptor dispatch rather than typed contracts.",
        "`config_update_registry.go` compensates with extensive manual patch field specs and merge rules per section, indicating abstraction friction at the update boundary.",
        "`defaults.go` constructs a large monolithic `SysConfig`, while consumers like `main.go` and other runtimes repeatedly snapshot individual slices of config, signaling that the top-level abstraction is too coarse.",
        "Typed convenience wrappers (`UpdateConnectivityConfig`, `UpdateRuntimeConfig`, etc.) coexist with dynamic `any` mutation, showing split abstraction direction."
      ],
      "suggestion": "Introduce typed section stores/services (for example `ConnectivityStore`, `RuntimeStore`, `AuthSessionStore`) and replace `any` section mutation with compile-time typed patch/update APIs; generate repetitive mapping where necessary.",
